name: Andrew Yang🧢🗽🇺🇸
tweet: This kind of failure makes me very angry and it should anger every New Yorker who has been waiting for a vaccine for either yourself or a loved one who is at elevated risk, or simply wants to feel like we are doing everything in our power to accelerate our recovery.

name: Andrew Yang🧢🗽🇺🇸

name: Andrew Yang🧢🗽🇺🇸
tweet: Our government is hopelessly behind on tech. Legislators haven’t had guidance since 1995 when they got rid of the Office of Technology Assessment. The average Senator is 62. Speeches won’t do much against trillions of dollars of financial incentives.

name: Andrew Yang🧢🗽🇺🇸
tweet: The big tech companies are essentially quasi-governments unto themselves at this point - the problem is their decisions are driven by maximizing ad revenue, user engagement and profit growth. That’s not the set of incentives you want when deciding what millions regard as truth.

name: Andrew Yang🧢🗽🇺🇸
tweet: There is an opportunity here to support artists, musicians and creatives as well whose work right now the market is ignoring. One element of this ought to be a degree of support for those whose work tries to elevate and inform rather than divide and denigrate.

name: Andrew Yang🧢🗽🇺🇸
tweet: The basic problem is that social media creators and companies are rewarded for having more extreme and untrue content. The goal should be to change or balance the incentives. Tech, government, media and NGOs need to collaborate on this to support fact-supported journalism.

name: Andrew Yang🧢🗽🇺🇸
tweet: The most difficult and important is to overhaul social media. We need federal data ownership legislation mirrored after the CPRA in California. There should be ad-free versions of every platform. Section 230 should be amended to not include content that is amplified by algorithm.

name: Andrew Yang🧢🗽🇺🇸
tweet: For Cable News we should revive the Fairness Doctrine which the FCC had on the books until 1985 that required that you show both sides of a political issue. It was repealed by Reagan. If there was ever a time to bring it back it’s now.

name: Andrew Yang🧢🗽🇺🇸
tweet: The easiest one to address is reopening local papers. There is a bill in Congress - the Local Journalism Sustainability Act from @davidcicilline and others - that would help support thousands of local publications. Congress should pass it immediately.

name: Andrew Yang🧢🗽🇺🇸
tweet: There are 3 problems with our media that are fueling polarization: 1. The closing of 2,000 local papers, which are typically not very partisan; 2. Cable news maximizing audience share by adopting political stances (Fox); and 3. Social media’s supercharging of conspiracy theories.

name: Andrew Yang🧢🗽🇺🇸
tweet: Polarization and violence will continue to rise unless we address social media’s cultivation of extremity and conspiracy theories. Fake news spreads 6 times more powerfully than truth on social media. That is a landscape that will breed mistrust and hatred.

name: Andrew Yang🧢🗽🇺🇸
tweet: Civilization is not guaranteed. It needs investment and replenishment.

name: Andrew Yang🧢🗽🇺🇸
tweet: I think too many journalists have been conditioned to be adaptable and long-suffering so when the rug gets pulled out from under you you try to keep it positive. “We will adapt.” Fuck that. The model is breaking and leaving us all out to dry.   Fucking say it so we can fix it.

name: Andrew Yang🧢🗽🇺🇸
tweet: @samstein And yes I have some ideas.

name: Andrew Yang🧢🗽🇺🇸
tweet: @samstein Anyone objectively looking at it has to despair for the future of journalism because our attention has become diffuse and cheap and consumers are largely conditioned not to pay for content. Instead of celebrating the few hardy exceptions we have to mend the system.

name: Andrew Yang🧢🗽🇺🇸
tweet: @samstein Literally thousands of journalists have seen their colleagues get washed out with the tide of digitization and consolidation. Tech titans buy major media outlets as high-brow indulgences. The market is compressing the value of journalism and we are all suffering for it.

name: Andrew Yang🧢🗽🇺🇸
tweet: @JHWeissmann The NYTimes is literally one newspaper and the biggest. Congratulations. Talk to the 1,000 communities who have lost their paper.

name: Andrew Yang🧢🗽🇺🇸
tweet: @samstein If there’s a young person thinking about journalism as a field, more and more people in the industry try to steer them away.  The winner-take-all economic dynamics are very much in effect but there are fewer and fewer winners.  It’s a disaster over time.

name: Andrew Yang🧢🗽🇺🇸
tweet: @samstein Thanks Sam. I think journalists should go harder after the industry issues you do see. It’s harder and harder to make a living in a field that is vital to our future. I’m pro-journalist and think that you all have an increasingly difficult and impossible job. We have to change it

tweet: @Moonalice I’m for lobbying for better laws. This is a way to get people excited to do so. Simply lobbying against the tech companies won’t work without millions of excited people. A data dividend is galvanizing - and will deliver economic value into people’s hands when they need it most.

name: Andrew Yang🧢🗽🇺🇸

name: Andrew Yang🧢🗽🇺🇸
tweet: Aren’t you sick of getting messages from companies you know you never signed up for? It’s because your data keeps getting sold and resold. It has to stop. We can enforce your data property rights - and give us all back our autonomy and data dignity.  https://t.co/q5fZFkEqQ7

name: Andrew Yang🧢🗽🇺🇸

name: Andrew Yang🧢🗽🇺🇸
tweet: The tech giants and data brokers are making tens of billions of dollars a year off of our data. Facebook alone is now a $650 billion company. How much of that should you be getting? Let’s find out - and fight for what you deserve.  https://t.co/H3c7Zx87Ak @ddpforall #paythepeople

tweet: It’s very hard to identify the relevant businesses. Some of them are very small. You would need a disaster relief type effort in every community. Or you would have to make reaources very freely available. The 2nd option is much better. But the recovery process will not be easy.

name: Andrew Yang🧢🗽🇺🇸
tweet: The question is how do you 1. Identify that business 2. support that business reopening and 3. somehow make them whole again. A loan actually just means they are still in the hole, which they may never climb out of. They might never reopen.

name: Andrew Yang🧢🗽🇺🇸
tweet: Here’s the problem - the average small business is barely making ends meet in normal times. Cut off 2-3 months of revenue and they are in a DEEP hole. Then when the business reopens the hole remains. Plus it takes a while to get fully revved up again. Many will never recover.

name: Andrew Yang🧢🗽🇺🇸
tweet: Anyone who understands the pervasive financial insecurity facing millions of Americans would know that we need drastic measures right now to avoid unbelievable levels of hardship and suffering as reality sets in.

name: Andrew Yang🧢🗽🇺🇸
tweet: Families can hole up for a week. But what about a month? 3 months? Bookings and events are being canceled months in advance. We should be planning for an extended period as the dearth of testing makes it hard to give the all clear sign.

name: Andrew Yang🧢🗽🇺🇸
tweet: A recession is guaranteed at this point. The question is how deep, how painful, what is the human toll?  If we do not do something dramatic people’s savings will dry up quickly and there will be many families in desperate circumstances in a matter of days.

name: Andrew Yang🧢🗽🇺🇸
tweet: This is not a fiscal problem this is a demand problem as the economy will slow to a crawl with the coronavirus. The question is how do you support baseline demand and give families the ability to weather this period? The only answer is to put cash into people’s hands quickly.
